    <div class="article-intro"><div class="article-hero"><img src="/assets/visuals/en-feature-premium-1600.webp" width="1280" height="720" alt="VeVolt economy dashboard comparing electric charging costs" fetchpriority="high"></div><header class="article-header"><p class="eyebrow"><span class="signal"></span>VeVolt guide</p><h1>Electric car versus gasoline: how to compare cost per kilometer</h1><p class="lede">A fair comparison uses the same distance and real local prices. Comparing a full battery with a full fuel tank hides the different capacity and efficiency of each vehicle.</p><p class="article-meta">Updated 18/07/2026 · 9 min read</p></header></div>
    <div class="article-layout"><div class="article-body"><section><h2>Calculate the electric cost</h2><p>Multiply electric consumption in kWh per 100 km by the effective price per kWh, including losses and recurring charging fees when relevant.</p></section><section><h2>Calculate the fuel cost</h2><p>Divide the fuel price per liter by the vehicle&#39;s real kilometers per liter. Use your own driving pattern rather than only laboratory figures.</p><ul><li>Same distance</li><li>Real electricity price</li><li>Real fuel price</li><li>Observed consumption</li><li>Comparable driving conditions</li></ul></section><section><h2>Compare a meaningful period</h2><p>Compare a month or several similar trips and remember that energy cost is only one part of total ownership. Maintenance, insurance, depreciation and taxes are separate decisions.</p></section><section><h2>Frequently asked questions</h2><div class="faq-list"><details class="faq-item"><summary>Is electricity always cheaper per kilometer?</summary><p>It often is, but local tariffs, fast-charging use and vehicle efficiency can change the result.</p></details><details class="faq-item"><summary>Does VeVolt calculate total ownership cost?</summary><p>No. Its economy records focus on energy, charging cost and fuel comparison.</p></details></div></section></div>
